.

.
Perfect when shared with good company, forget the cutlery and go fingers in.

Tire lizi√©

Sky blue or lavender blue nespresso pods paired with star shaped üßø! That nespresso pod happens to be my favourite colour, I think!
To me, Tire lizi√© is the action of going to an elder matriarch (my mom or grand mother) and ask them to pass salt around my head 7 times. It is an extremely personal moment between my grandma and myself. I tend to do it when I’ve had chronic headaches, anxiety attacks or just a feeling of malaise! To be very honest, I’m sure that it isn’t very Islamic, it is rather more cultural. Nazar üßø or evil eye is an Islamic concept though, we acknowledge the evil from envy, jealousy or ill wishing. In islam you would rather protect yourself through prayers than other acts. 
The Nazar isn’t limited to Islamic cultures or countries, it is a greatly respected within Turkey, Greece, Cyprus and many other middle eastern countries.
The important discussion though, isn’t if you believe in it or not. Rather, it is about whether you are open to people who have other beliefs than you. Can you make this world a safe space for them and their practices. And are you ready to learn from them and from beliefs that you do not share. :)

node.text:
Do you know how it feels to not to be loved back from the person you gave your heart to?
Do you know how much it hurts when you are forced to keep your tears behind a big smile? Hiding.
Don't you know this feeling that shatters you in pieces comes at a price? A price of never being able to love back again.

We were moon and stars. Always together but never close enough.
Or wait, we were sun and moon.
Always there for eachother,
For without another, one's existence would vanish.
But would never be able to meet.

We were the perfect blue vase and the beautiful purple flowers.
So pretty, but not together.
For they would dull each other's spark.

I now know how it feels like to be broken and for the wounds to be left unattended.
Maybe you could nurse it.

But now, I want us to move on, to carry on.
But promise me one thing,
The day when we shall meet again
You will have time for me.
The day we shall hug again,
You shall carry the same warmth.
The day we shall see each other again,
Our eyes will get as excited as they use to get every other time.

But, for now
I lay here, 
Lifeless doing nothing
But carving words of our love 
Of our destiny
And of us.

VIRTUAL SHOOT

When this year started, I think, no one would have thought about the term Virtual Shoot. Then horror which we used to read in past came in reality for this generation... Pandemic. 
Lockdown was imposed in short interval notice and in a snap sound of fingers, many found themselves jobless, trapped inside. Privileged as me just had to get ourselves keep confined to our spaces. Real struggle was for them whose life started daily with sunrise and bread earned by long day hard work. Now there was no work.
As a photographers' perspective, shoots got cancelled, project delayed or denied. After a few days of not shooting, we started searching way to pursue passion. Business meetings started on conference video calls. Few photographers came with a temporary solution of shooting on video calls. Facetime shoots, WhatsApp Call shoots, Google video shoots, Skype shoot came in existence... in a shell, Virtual Shoots. Ofcourse not good as actual shoot, but "...dil ko khush rakhne ko ghalib ye khayal achchha hai...", it became a trend amongst photographers.
After initial denial, me too thought to give it a try. Talked to few people connected with me. Now I am sharing few results. 
I won't call myself as Photographer for these shots, just a director.
